mies. Over the years, policy, politics, and social turmoil shaped the rural, mountainous regions of Peru until violent unrest, perpetrated by the Shining Path and other revolutionary groups, unveiled the extent, limits, and fractures of a century-long process of rural state formation. Examining the conflicts between one rural community and the many iterations of statehood in the central sierra of Peru, The Rural State offers a fresh perspective on how the Andes became la sierra, how pueblos became comunidades, and how indígenas became campesinos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAgriculture and statezPeruxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peopleszPeruzSierraxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aLand reformxSocial aspectszPeruzSierraxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aLatin American History, Andean History, Peruvian History, Rural History, Agrarian History, Environmental History, Agrarian Reform, Political Violence, Agrarian Conflict, Rural Conflict, Revolutions, Peasant Politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32628240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477326299423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477326299/original  a978-3-11-076651-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK